00:02:49.234 --> 00:02:53.234
Let's talk about what
conservatorship is, first.

00:02:55.812 --> 00:02:58.145
It's a legal process, right?

00:02:59.251 --> 00:03:00.975
You have the court,

00:03:00.975 --> 00:03:03.366
you have an individual with a disability,

00:03:03.366 --> 00:03:06.229
and the court appoints someone else

00:03:06.229 --> 00:03:09.812
to be making decisions
for that individual.

00:03:11.621 --> 00:03:14.623
The legal standard for doing that

00:03:14.623 --> 00:03:17.183
is that the individual is unable to

00:03:17.183 --> 00:03:20.587
provide for his or her personal needs,

00:03:20.587 --> 00:03:23.430
being able to provide
food, clothing, shelter,

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:25.318
even with supports,

00:03:25.318 --> 00:03:27.095
that's important,

00:03:27.095 --> 00:03:29.654
and also important, there are no

00:03:29.654 --> 00:03:32.119
less restrictive options available.

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:34.286
I'm forgetting to do this.

00:03:47.003 --> 00:03:49.902
You're moving these for
me, aren't you? Okay.

00:03:49.902 --> 00:03:52.735
(audience laughs)

00:03:53.902 --> 00:03:58.420
The conservator controls
essentially everything

00:03:58.420 --> 00:04:02.026
when it is a plenary conservatorship.

00:04:02.026 --> 00:04:04.307
There are conservatorships that

00:04:04.307 --> 00:04:06.925
are supposed to be more restrictive,

00:04:06.925 --> 00:04:11.384
that they only control a
certain part of someone's life.

00:04:11.384 --> 00:04:15.552
But even after decades
of advocacy to improve

00:04:15.552 --> 00:04:18.628
the way we implement conservatorships,

00:04:18.628 --> 00:04:21.479
we find that that
generally doesn't happen.

00:04:21.479 --> 00:04:23.293
That plenary conservatorships are the

00:04:23.293 --> 00:04:26.005
default mode for most judges.

00:04:26.005 --> 00:04:27.219
It's understandable.

00:04:27.219 --> 00:04:29.784
They're worried about what would happen

00:04:29.784 --> 00:04:33.053
if they don't provide enough protection.

00:04:33.053 --> 00:04:36.425
There's a very paternalistic culture

00:04:36.425 --> 00:04:39.258
in conservatorship probate courts.

00:04:40.978 --> 00:04:43.228
But what this means is that

00:04:44.302 --> 00:04:46.940
the person who's under conservatorship,

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:50.492
essentially ceases to
exist as a legal entity.

00:04:50.492 --> 00:04:52.866
The conservator takes away

00:04:52.866 --> 00:04:56.533
any possibility of
decision making, legally.

00:04:58.567 --> 00:05:01.440
We've had situations in
which the conservator

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:04.807
not only controls the money
and the living situation,

00:05:04.807 --> 00:05:08.974
but also whether or not to
go to religious observances,

00:05:10.273 --> 00:05:13.766
whether the individual is able to see

00:05:13.766 --> 00:05:16.433
or refuse to see family members,

00:05:18.098 --> 00:05:22.450
and whether the individual
is able to marry

00:05:22.450 --> 00:05:24.617
or make medical decisions.

00:05:25.523 --> 00:05:29.023
Next slide, and I'm gonna do it this time.

00:05:30.044 --> 00:05:32.211
From the ACLU perspective,

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:37.127
we care about this because it is the most

00:05:37.127 --> 00:05:40.539
complete deprivation of civil liberties

00:05:40.539 --> 00:05:42.903
aside from the death penalty,

00:05:42.903 --> 00:05:45.820
which Claude Pepper acknowledged in

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:50.392
congressional review of
this issue years ago.

00:05:50.392 --> 00:05:54.559
But we have made fairly
little progress since then.

00:05:55.511 --> 00:05:58.179
From a parent's perspective,

00:05:58.179 --> 00:06:01.187
civil liberties probably
aren't that important.

00:06:01.187 --> 00:06:04.697
What's much more important is the way that

00:06:04.697 --> 00:06:09.546
the conservatorship will
affect the child's life.

00:06:09.546 --> 00:06:11.963
We've already gone through...

00:06:22.411 --> 00:06:26.131
We've already gone through
the fact that the court

00:06:26.131 --> 00:06:28.082
appoints the conservator.

00:06:28.082 --> 00:06:30.501
But I should also point out

00:06:30.501 --> 00:06:33.625
that the court can remove the conservator.

00:06:33.625 --> 00:06:36.749
We have had situations in which

00:06:36.749 --> 00:06:39.553
the court has appointed a parent

00:06:39.553 --> 00:06:43.754
because that was the plan for the family.

00:06:43.754 --> 00:06:45.921
But then the parent is resisting

00:06:45.921 --> 00:06:48.515
what the court is
ordering the parent to do,

00:06:48.515 --> 00:06:52.265
and decides, "okay fine. I'm
removing you as conservator,

00:06:52.265 --> 00:06:56.165
and I'm appointing a
professional conservator."

00:06:56.165 --> 00:06:58.616
Professional conservators often don't have

00:06:58.616 --> 00:07:01.354
a lot of time to get
to know the individual.

00:07:01.354 --> 00:07:03.187
They often go by rote,

00:07:04.084 --> 00:07:08.759
and often will default to
institutional placements

00:07:08.759 --> 00:07:11.342
when other options aren't easy.

00:07:14.034 --> 00:07:15.869
The other piece is that,

00:07:15.869 --> 00:07:20.859
for many of the population
that we're most interested in,

00:07:20.859 --> 00:07:24.321
folks with developmental disabilities,

00:07:24.321 --> 00:07:27.571
decision making can increase with time.

00:07:28.553 --> 00:07:32.712
Conservatorship may be
something that isn't

00:07:32.712 --> 00:07:35.220
that bad at the beginning,

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:39.387
when it's imposed when the
individual is 18 or 19.

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:44.801
But it's not something
that's easy to reverse.

00:07:44.801 --> 00:07:48.091
Courts really, really don't like

00:07:48.091 --> 00:07:52.008
taking someone out from
under a conservatorship

00:07:54.089 --> 00:07:56.277
once it's in place.

00:07:56.277 --> 00:08:00.387
That person at 40 or 45 may
be living independently,

00:08:00.387 --> 00:08:03.804
may be working at a job almost full time,

00:08:05.548 --> 00:08:07.661
but is still under conservatorship.

00:08:07.661 --> 00:08:09.791
We've worked with folks in this situation

00:08:09.791 --> 00:08:12.420
and found it very difficult to get them

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:15.337
out from under the conservatorship.

00:08:19.702 --> 00:08:22.245
Again, from the parent's perspective,

00:08:22.245 --> 00:08:24.620
this isn't just a
problem in the long term,

00:08:24.620 --> 00:08:28.067
it's also a problem in
terms of what is best

00:08:28.067 --> 00:08:29.264
for the individual.

00:08:29.264 --> 00:08:31.104
For the individual's perspective

00:08:31.104 --> 00:08:32.566
it's a problem in terms of

00:08:32.566 --> 00:08:35.149
what's best for the individual.

00:08:36.472 --> 00:08:41.458
We all learn how to make
decisions by making mistakes.

00:08:41.458 --> 00:08:44.174
We all learn how to make decisions by

00:08:44.174 --> 00:08:46.886
practicing making decisions.

00:08:46.886 --> 00:08:49.556
If someone is making the decisions for you

00:08:49.556 --> 00:08:51.821
that skill is much harder to develop.

00:08:51.821 --> 00:08:53.404
It may not develop.

00:08:54.817 --> 00:08:57.980
Most studies that have looked at this

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:01.398
show that folks who have that practice,

00:09:01.398 --> 00:09:04.094
who have been able to
exercise decision making

00:09:04.094 --> 00:09:06.352
and self-determination,

00:09:06.352 --> 00:09:10.785
are in fact better able
to protect themselves

00:09:10.785 --> 00:09:12.618
from abuse or neglect.

00:09:13.541 --> 00:09:15.638
They know who to go to,
they know who to ask,

00:09:15.638 --> 00:09:17.638
they know how to say no.

00:09:22.122 --> 00:09:23.707
Let's talk for a few moments

00:09:23.707 --> 00:09:25.517
about supported decision-making.

00:09:25.517 --> 00:09:29.390
Does anyone want to try
and define it for me?

00:09:29.390 --> 00:09:30.307
Brave soul?

00:09:32.386 --> 00:09:36.553
You wouldn't be wrong, because
(audience laughs)

00:09:37.667 --> 00:09:40.731
supported decision-making
has so many definitions.

00:09:40.731 --> 00:09:42.981
It's a very broad category.

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:47.397
What we like about it most at the ACLU

00:09:47.397 --> 00:09:49.807
is that it allows people with disabilities

00:09:49.807 --> 00:09:51.613
to retain their legal status,

00:09:51.613 --> 00:09:53.878
to retain their civil liberties.

00:09:53.878 --> 00:09:57.646
The idea is that an individual chooses

00:09:57.646 --> 00:10:00.345
one to sometimes three or more

00:10:00.345 --> 00:10:02.275
people who they trust

00:10:02.275 --> 00:10:06.442
to help them with the
process of making decisions.

00:10:07.632 --> 00:10:10.360
Because it is a less restrictive

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:13.083
alternative to conservatorship,

00:10:13.083 --> 00:10:15.044
under California law

00:10:15.044 --> 00:10:17.244
we believe it should be tried

00:10:17.244 --> 00:10:20.077
before imposing a conservatorship.

00:10:25.131 --> 00:10:28.964
A little more about
supported decision-making.

00:10:30.371 --> 00:10:33.692
The key piece of supported decision-making

00:10:33.692 --> 00:10:36.803
is recognizing that we don't have

00:10:36.803 --> 00:10:39.907
an on/off switch with capacity.

00:10:39.907 --> 00:10:41.907
It's not all or nothing.

00:10:43.170 --> 00:10:45.000
People's ability to make decisions

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.833
depend on the context,

00:10:48.086 --> 00:10:50.175
depend on the issue,

00:10:50.175 --> 00:10:54.396
depend on how they're doing
at that moment in time.

00:10:54.396 --> 00:10:56.300
We all use supported decision-making.

00:10:56.300 --> 00:11:00.900
I use it for everything from
making major medical decisions

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:05.230
to certainly what I'm gonna
do with my adolescent.

00:11:05.230 --> 00:11:07.333
(audience laughs)

00:11:07.333 --> 00:11:10.376
Even whether I'm gonna buy
these dining room chairs

00:11:10.376 --> 00:11:13.043
versus those dining room chairs.

00:11:14.098 --> 00:11:15.348
The idea behind

00:11:18.499 --> 00:11:21.696
the more formal designation
of supported decision-making

00:11:21.696 --> 00:11:24.779
for people with disabilities, is that

00:11:27.199 --> 00:11:29.532
the agreement is recognized.

00:11:31.317 --> 00:11:34.575
That both sides understand that

00:11:34.575 --> 00:11:37.492
for these areas of decision making,

00:11:39.022 --> 00:11:42.355
I'm gonna go to these people for advice.

00:11:44.923 --> 00:11:49.442
There are formal documents
that can be signed.

00:11:49.442 --> 00:11:51.567
We have examples of them on our website

00:11:51.567 --> 00:11:55.734
on the ACLU, which is at
the end of your PowerPoint.

00:11:56.622 --> 00:12:00.289
But we also have more
informal arrangements.

00:12:01.829 --> 00:12:03.981
The good thing about
supported decision-making

00:12:03.981 --> 00:12:07.197
is that you don't have to go to court,

00:12:07.197 --> 00:12:11.364
and as your relationships change,
as your capacities change,

00:12:12.232 --> 00:12:15.399
as your opinions and interests change,

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:20.244
you can change who is
providing you the advice,

00:12:20.244 --> 00:12:22.994
who is providing you the support.

00:12:28.996 --> 00:12:32.170
Some of the ways that we encourage people

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:35.193
to think about providing support

00:12:35.193 --> 00:12:38.904
really breaks down into
how decisions are made.

00:12:38.904 --> 00:12:41.071
Every decision has a goal.

00:12:42.497 --> 00:12:46.131
That needs to be clear at the outset.

00:12:46.131 --> 00:12:48.214
Then identifying options,

00:12:49.642 --> 00:12:53.072
evaluating the pros and
cons of those options,

00:12:53.072 --> 00:12:54.763
reminding the individual of

00:12:54.763 --> 00:12:58.165
what values they bring to the decision,

00:12:58.165 --> 00:13:01.215
and finally making the decision.

00:13:01.215 --> 00:13:04.579
Supporters should be willing to help

00:13:04.579 --> 00:13:08.881
with articulating any of
those first four issues:

00:13:08.881 --> 00:13:11.040
what's the goal, what are the options,

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:14.303
pros and cons, what
are the values at play.

00:13:14.303 --> 00:13:17.293
But the idea is that the individual

00:13:17.293 --> 00:13:19.067
is the person who makes that fifth,

00:13:19.067 --> 00:13:22.484
final step of what the final decision is.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:27.028
Supporters also may be really key in

00:13:27.028 --> 00:13:30.534
translating complicated
ideas into plain language.

00:13:30.534 --> 00:13:34.256
One of the things that
we did at the ACLU is

00:13:34.256 --> 00:13:38.954
translate powers of attorney
into plain language.

00:13:38.954 --> 00:13:40.609
So powers of attorney for healthcare,

00:13:40.609 --> 00:13:43.276
powers of attorney for finances,

00:13:44.507 --> 00:13:45.507
permissions,

00:13:46.536 --> 00:13:51.168
HIPPA releases translated
into plain language.

00:13:51.168 --> 00:13:55.001
Permission to work with
the educational system

00:13:56.282 --> 00:13:57.865
once a child is 18,

00:13:59.772 --> 00:14:02.296
translated into plain language.

00:14:02.296 --> 00:14:04.587
With these plain language documents,

00:14:04.587 --> 00:14:08.754
almost anything that you
need legal authorization for

00:14:09.726 --> 00:14:11.876
you can use and talk with

00:14:11.876 --> 00:14:15.126
an individual with a disability through

00:14:16.145 --> 00:14:18.312
if they want that support.

00:14:19.561 --> 00:14:24.088
Finally, helping to
communicate wishes to others.

00:14:24.088 --> 00:14:25.671
This may be because

00:14:27.645 --> 00:14:30.395
the individual has cerebral palsy

00:14:31.511 --> 00:14:33.966
and it is a skill that's developed

00:14:33.966 --> 00:14:36.560
to be able to understand
what they're saying,

00:14:36.560 --> 00:14:39.529
or it may be because of a lot
what Rudy was talking about

00:14:39.529 --> 00:14:42.478
in that you've spent enough
time with the individual

00:14:42.478 --> 00:14:45.984
that you have a better guesswork system

00:14:45.984 --> 00:14:49.734
to be able to convey
their values and wishes.

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:57.826
How do we know if
supported decision-making

00:14:57.826 --> 00:15:01.243
might work for the patients that you see?

00:15:02.419 --> 00:15:05.993
The first step is to acknowledge

00:15:05.993 --> 00:15:08.993
that there's a wide range of issues,

00:15:10.197 --> 00:15:14.157
and we don't have a "yes"
or "no" for each of them.

00:15:14.157 --> 00:15:18.209
The second is to help
them identify which areas

00:15:18.209 --> 00:15:20.334
they might need support in

00:15:20.334 --> 00:15:23.084
and help them find who they might

00:15:24.046 --> 00:15:26.379
use to provide that support.

00:15:30.669 --> 00:15:32.746
One of the things that I'm...

00:15:32.746 --> 00:15:34.692
I'm glad that we're doing
pretty well with time.

00:15:34.692 --> 00:15:38.171
I want to spend a fair
amount of time talking now

00:15:38.171 --> 00:15:41.781
about a new tool for
competency evaluations.

00:15:41.781 --> 00:15:45.086
Those of you who've done
competency evaluations,

00:15:45.086 --> 00:15:48.255
what do you usually use to do them?

00:15:48.255 --> 00:15:51.005
I really do want you to speak up.

00:15:52.743 --> 00:15:54.160
Someone be brave.

00:15:57.545 --> 00:16:01.462
(comment from man in audience)

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:28.441
- So you're talking about
a competency evaluation

00:16:28.441 --> 00:16:30.378
for one particular decision,

00:16:30.378 --> 00:16:31.421
and you try and make sure that

00:16:31.421 --> 00:16:33.456
you understand that one decision.

00:16:33.456 --> 00:16:34.695
Okay, great.

00:16:34.695 --> 00:16:36.009
(comment from audience)

00:16:36.009 --> 00:16:37.092
Great, okay.

00:16:38.642 --> 00:16:41.584
Has anyone done competency evaluations

00:16:41.584 --> 00:16:43.417
for a conservatorship?

00:16:44.815 --> 00:16:48.898
(comment from woman in audience)

00:16:50.571 --> 00:16:53.970
- In California, guardianship applies

00:16:53.970 --> 00:16:56.636
to people under 18, youth,

00:16:56.636 --> 00:17:01.198
and conservatorship applies
to people over 18, adults.

00:17:01.198 --> 00:17:03.948
I'm talking about people over 18.

00:17:05.216 --> 00:17:06.627
In the rest of the country,

00:17:06.627 --> 00:17:08.885
guardianship generally applies to adults.

00:17:08.885 --> 00:17:13.052
It's confusing for those
of us who work nationally.

00:17:14.714 --> 00:17:18.797
(comment from woman in audience)

00:17:42.352 --> 00:17:44.337
- Okay. That's really important

00:17:44.337 --> 00:17:45.573
and we're gonna come back to that.

00:17:45.573 --> 00:17:48.864
There's someone whose
hand was up back here.

00:17:48.864 --> 00:17:52.947
(comment from woman in audience)

00:17:58.663 --> 00:18:01.061
Their social situation.

00:18:01.061 --> 00:18:03.303
Their past medical history.

00:18:03.303 --> 00:18:04.886
Neurological exams.

00:18:06.293 --> 00:18:08.034
Ability to communicate.

